                                        "},{"type":"paragraph","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Take "},{"type":"text","text":"any","marks":[{"type":"bold"}]},{"type":"text","text":" 20 coins from the pile of 100 coins, and flip the pile over to get two equal piles - it really is that easy! For example, if you take 20 coins and 7 of them are gold facing up ways, then there will be 14 silver facing up ways coins, and also the other 14 gold facing up ways coins will be in the pile of 80 coins; if you flip the pile containing 20 coins, the 14 silver facing up ways coins will become 14 gold facing up ways coins, hence 2 piles containing an equal amount of gold facing up ways coins. This will work for any scenario, whether all the coins are in the pile of 20 coins, or none of them are in there."}]},{"type":"text","text":"



